description.value:
Fragmentary limestone base for a votive statue.

The intact portion of the statue is a rough ‘L’ shape. One broad side of the stone and the adjoining corner are heavily damaged, likely a result of breaking of the monument into fragments. On the uneven corner piece of stone is a small portion of incised text containing the ka symbol, suggesting that this portion of the statue was originally inscribed. The opposing sides of the stone are in a much greater state of preservation, with the largest side inscribed with three partial columns of text, reading from left to right. The third line is now mostly lost, and a large gouge to the stone has erased the concluding signs of the final two lines. The final slim side of the base also contains a single column of text, and both inscribed sections of the statue have a horizontal line of continuous text around the base. Based on the layout and orientation, this slim portion of inscription likely belonged to the front section of the statue,… (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value: Hollow terracotta figure of Harpokratis in a long feminine tunic, standing on a convex-faced plinth with horizontal mouldings, and leaning on a pier with mouldings at top and bottom. Her finger is to her mouth, she holds a cornucopia against her left shoulder, and rests her arm against a falcon standing on top of the altar. She has a full head of hair with a wreath defining her face, and wears a small Double Crown, largely lost; she may have crescent earrings, but they might be the lowest elements of the wreath. On the face of the pier, certainly inscribed in modern times, is a group of hieroglyphs. Back un-modelled; circular vent, broken at one side; irregular hole broken through below it. Two-piece mould. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt, with brown surface. Traces of a white dressing.

description.value: Wallet (?), flat sleeve of plain cotton cloth on a stiff base of strips of palm leaf. The palm placed lengthwise and crosswise and held together with paired cotton threads. The cloth covering, of two pieces of cotton cut on the bias and seamed together down the centre held onto the palm by a network of stretched and couched cotton threads clearly intended to be partly decorative. Around one end, stem stitching in a thicker thread.
